CO2 ELEVATION, CANOPY PHOTOSYNTHESIS, ANDOPTIMAL LEAF AREA INDEX

T. Hirose, 
D. D. Ackerly, 
M. B. Traw,

Abstract

We studied the effects of CO2 elevation on leaf and canopy photosynthesis and optimal leaf area index (LAI) for stands of the annual species Abutilon theophrasti and Ambrosia artemisiifolia. Leaf photosynthesis was modeled as a function of photosynthetic photon flux density (PPFD) and nitrogen content per unit leaf area (NL). There was a curvilinear relationship between the light-saturated rates of leaf photosynthesis (Pmax) and NL. CO2 elevation significantly increased Pmax as a function of NL in both species. Dark respiration (Rd) was linearly correlated with NL. CO2 elevation slightly but significantly increased Rd in Abutilon, while it had no significant effect on Rd in Ambrosia. The initial slope of a light-response curve was determined from quantum yield (φabs) multiplied by leaf absorptance and then calibrated against NL. Daily canopy photosynthesis, calculated by integration of leaf photosynthesis with the actual distribution of leaf area, leaf N, and PPFD within a canopy, showed fairly good agreement with the canopy photosynthesis estimated from growth analysis. CO2 elevation increased canopy photosynthesis by 30–50%. Based on the leaf photosynthesis model for Abutilon, we calculated daily canopy photosynthesis for a given LAI and N availability, in which N was assumed to be distributed optimally within a leaf canopy to maximize daily canopy photosynthesis. An optimal LAI to maximize daily canopy photosynthesis was obtained for each level of N availability and this optimum increased with increasing N availability. Contrary to the often predicted increase in LAI with CO2 elevation, the optimum LAI did not increase at high CO2 when N availability was limited. Two factors were suggested to be involved in counteracting the increase in LAI in a high-CO2 world. One is the higher φabs of plants grown in elevated CO2, which makes leaves in the canopy more N limited, favors higher NL and thus lowers optimal LAI. The other is the higher Rd in elevated CO2, which leads to higher light compensation points, and lowers optimal LAI.

Introduction

Elevation in atmospheric CO2 concentration is believed to increase dry mass productivity of C3 plants (Bazzaz 1990). Increase in productivity of a plant canopy may result from increasing leaf area index (LAI, total leaf area per unit ground area) as well as from increasing photosynthetic activity of leaves. Conflicting results, however, have been reported on the effect of CO2 elevation on leaf area development, e.g., LAI increased with CO2 elevation in the canopy of perennial ryegrass (Nijs et al. 1988), soybean (Cambell et al. 1990), and rice (Rowland-Bamford et al. 1991), while it remained the same in artificial tropical forest ecosystems (Körner and Arnone 1992). Studying the effect of CO2 elevation on canopy development in two co-occurring annuals, we showed a strong correlation between LAI and aboveground plant nitrogen (Hirose et al. 1996b). Since there was no significant difference between CO2 levels in the regression of LAI against aboveground N, we hypothesized that leaf area development is controlled primarily by the amount of N available for plant growth. This hypothesis suggests that the LAI would increase with CO2 elevation if and only if N uptake from the soil is simultaneously increased, e.g., due to increased substrate supply for root growth. In order to further investigate this hypothesis, in this paper we present a model of canopy photosynthesis, based on the distribution of leaf N and photosynthetic photon flux density (PPFD) through the canopy, and we analyze the effects of CO2 elevation and N availability on canopy photosynthesis and LAI. The gradient of leaf N that develops in parallel with a gradient of light climate is incorporated into the model, because it strongly influences canopy photosynthesis (Hirose and Werger 1987b).

In this paper we first show leaf N distribution in the canopy of monospecific and mixed stands of two co-occurring annual species (Abutilon theophrasti and Ambrosia artemisiifolia) established under ambient (360 μL/L) and elevated (700 μL/L) CO2 conditions. Second, we model leaf photosynthesis as a function of leaf N and incident PPFD, taking account of the effect of CO2 elevation on the light-saturated rate, dark respiration, and the initial slope of light-response curve. Third, canopy photosynthesis is calculated for monospecific and mixed stands of the two species established under ambient and elevated CO2 conditions. These different combinations provide a variety of canopy structures that are used to validate our canopy photosynthesis model. And finally, we determine optimal LAI that maximizes daily canopy photosynthesis with a given amount of N for leaf growth, where N was distributed optimally in the canopy. We show that the optimal LAI does not increase with CO2 elevation when the availability of N for leaf growth is limited.

Materials and Methods

Determination of canopy structure

The experiment to determine canopy structure was conducted at the Harvard University OEB Glasshouse in March–May 1994, using seeds of Abutilon and Ambrosia from an Illinois seed supply company (Hirose et al. 1996b). Seedlings were germinated and grown in round pots (0.1 m in diameter and 0.1 m deep) in either an ambient (360 μL/L) or elevated (700 μL/L) CO2 atmosphere. Two-hundred and forty pots were placed contiguously in a square arrangement giving a density of 100 pots/m2 in each of six CO2 and temperature-controled zones. Plants were grown in pots to exclude root competition between individuals, allowing us to focus on interference in light interception and to reduce size variation among individuals. Adjacent zones were assigned to different CO2 atmosphere treatments and were blocked together, for a total of three blocks. Temperature was maintained at 25°C day and 20°C night. Lighting was supplemented by halogen bulbs to extend day length (14 h). The photosynthetically active photon flux density (400–700 nm, PPFD) was up to 1200 μmol·m−2·s−1 on clear days.

During the 2nd and 3rd wks following germination, plants were thinned to one per pot. Plants were fertilized on days 24, 27, and 32 with 55 mL of full-strength nutrient solution (0.2 g/L for N, P, and K). Thus, each plant received 82.5 mg each of N, P, and K in total. Each pot had a saucer, so that nutrients that leached from the soil remained in the water available to the pot, and so that pot water content could be maintained at field capacity. When the plants were 3 wk old, they were arranged to form either monospecific or mixed (1:1) stands of Abutilon and Ambrosia. In each stand, there were 18 plants arranged in a rectangle (3 × 6 pots). In the mixed stand, there were nine plants of each species distributed in a checkerboard pattern. Surrounding each stand there was a single row of border plants in the same arrangement. The three stands were arranged east to west with the narrow sides adjacent. The resulting rectangle (5 × 24 pots) was bordered by shade cloth during the 6th wk to eliminate edge effects. The shade cloth wall, a black layer sandwiched between two white layers, was set level with the top of the canopy and adjusted as the canopy height increased.

In order to obtain harvests of stands at two ages, we germinated a second set of seeds 2 wk after the first set. The same techniques were used as for the first set of seedlings. Plants of the younger group were fertilized on days 26, 29, and 35 with the same amount of fertilizer as the first stand. All of the plants of the two age groups were harvested together, when the plants in the older stands were 53 d old and the plants in the younger stands were 39 d old. Each day one of the three blocks was harvested. Before harvesting, stand light levels (PPFD) were measured at 0.05-m intervals from the ground with a line sensor (Sunfleck Ceptometer, Decagon, USA). The length of sensible part was reduced to 0.5 m with black tape to meet the size of the harvest area. The sensor was held horizontally during measurement and calibrated for the stand size. Relative PPFD was calculated against reference PPFD measured above the canopy with a point sensor (LI-185, LI-COR, Lincoln, Nebraska, USA), which was calibrated with the line sensor. Two measurements of light level were taken at each interval. Stand canopies were harvested from the top down in 0.05-m layers as measured from soil surface. At each layer, petioles and stems were combined. Leaf area of each layer was measured with a leaf area meter (LI-3000, LI-COR, Lincoln, Nebraska, USA). In the mixed stands, the plants of each species were harvested separately. Dry mass was determined after oven-drying at 50°C for >3 d. Dried plant materials were ground with a mill and their N contents were determined with a gas-chromatograph after combustion with circulating O2 (NC-analyzer Sumigraph NC-80, Shimadzu, Japan).

Determination of light-saturated rate, dark respiration, and the initial slope

In order to conduct detailed physiological measurements we established similar stands to those described above in 1995. Light-saturated rates of CO2 exchange and the rate of dark respiration were measured in situ for leaves of Abutilon and Ambrosia in the glasshouse with a portable closed-gas-exchange measurement system (LI-6200, LI-COR, Lincoln, Nebraska, USA). Volume of the leaf chamber was 250 mL. The CO2 concentration of the air at measurement was the same as that in which plants were grown. Air temperature in the leaf chamber was 26 ± 1°C. Measurement of the light-saturated rate of photosynthesis was done under sunny conditions with PPFD > 1000 μmol·m−2·s−1. Different leaves were used for measurement of dark respiration, which was done by wrapping the leaf chamber with a thick black cloth. Leaves were sampled from different heights along the stem, each representing a different leaf age and layer in the canopy. After leaf area measurement, leaf dry mass and N content were determined as described above. Rectangular hyperbolic equations were fitted to the relationship between leaf nitrogen per unit area (NL) and the light-saturated rate and linear equations fitted to the relationship between NL and dark respiration.

The initial slope of a light-response curve (φ) is a quantum yield (φabs) multiplied by leaf absorptance (Hikosaka and Terashima 1995). Quantum yield increases with increasing CO2 concentration (Ehleringer and Björkman 1977, Pearcy and Björkman 1983). We assumed φabs = 0.05 at the atmospheric CO2 concentration of 360 μL/L and φabs = 0.07 at 700 μL/L CO2, using data in Ehleringer and Björkman (1977). Leaf absorptance (α) was calculated following Evans (1994):
((1))
α = c/(c + 0.076)
where c is chlorophyll content per unit leaf area in millimoles per square meter. Chlorophyll content was measured with a chlorophyll meter (SPAD-502, Minolta, Japan). SPAD values were calibrated with independent determinations of chlorophyll content following the procedure of Moran (1982). SPAD values were also calibrated with NL and we obtained relationships between N and chlorophyll content, which were fitted to a nonrectangular hyperbola equation. Thus we could calculate the initial slope for a leaf with a given NL.
Leaf transmittance was calculated as a ratio of PPFD measured just below the leaf to that above the leaf and determined for Abutilon and Ambrosia grown under two CO2 conditions. Over the two species and two CO2 conditions, transmittance (τ) was described as a function of chlorophyll content (c, in micromoles per square meter):
((2))
τ = 0.41 exp(−4.0c)  (r2 = 0.98)

Modeling leaf and canopy photosynthesis

Pmax, Rd, and φ are functions of NL (see Determination of light-saturated rate ... above). θ = 0.8 was assumed as an average value taken from several previous studies (Hirose and Werger 1987a, Pons et al. 1990, Anten et al. 1995b). Thus CO2 exchange rates of leaves can be calculated based on NL and incident PPFD.

Statistics

There were three replicates of each treatment (i.e., monospecific and mixed stands established under ambient and elevated CO2 conditions of two harvests) in determining canopy structure, and their mean and standard error are presented. Analysis of variance (ANOVA) was used to test for main effects of species, age, CO2, interference, and their interactions. Analysis of covariance (ANCOVA) was used to test differences between the two CO2 levels in regressions of photosynthetic parameters against leaf N (Sokal and Rohlf 1981). Coefficients of determination (r2) were calculated as the square of the correlation coefficient between observed and expected values from regression. Treatment effects were considered significant if P < 0.05.

Results

Distribution of leaf nitrogen in the canopy

Fig. 1 shows the vertical distribution of leaf N per plant in the monospecific and mixed stands of Abutilon and Ambrosia grown under ambient (360 μL/L) and elevated (700 μL/L) CO2 conditions. CO2 elevation tended to shift leaf N distribution upward, reflecting the distribution of leaf area (Fig. 1 in Hirose et al. 1996b). Abutilon distributed their leaf N in upper layers of the canopy, while Ambrosia distributed leaf N more to lower layers. This pattern of N distribution did not change when the two species were grown in mixed stands. By day 39 Ambrosia had accumulated more than twice as much leaf N as Abutilon. However, total leaf N increased nearly threefold in Abutilon by day 53, resulting in significant ANOVA effects of species, age, and their interaction (Table 1).

Table 1. Summary of analysis of variance (ANOVA) for the effect of interference, species, age, CO2, and their interactions on leaf N per plant and N content per unit leaf area (NL). F values are presented.

Changes in leaf nitrogen per leaf area (NL) are shown as lines in Fig. 1. From day 39 through day 53, N was reallocated to the leaves at higher positions in the canopy. Leaves in top layers maintained the same levels of NL during canopy development, while leaves in the lower layers reduced NL considerably. Thus NL was distributed in the leaf canopy with steeper gradients on day 53 than on day 39. Of the two species, Ambrosia developed steeper gradients of NL than Abutilon. There was no significant effect of CO2 elevation on N reallocation. On average, Ambrosia had higher NL than Abutilon and both species decreased NL with age. There was also significant interaction of species × age (ANOVA; Table 1). CO2 elevation tended to decrease NL, though the effect was not statistically significant (see the effects of CO2 and Species × Age × CO2, Table 1).

Daily canopy photosynthesis

Daily rates of canopy photosynthesis were calculated based on the actual distribution of leaf area and leaf N (Fig. 1) with the leaf photosynthesis model presented above. Distribution of leaf area determines light climate in the canopy and leaf N determines photosynthetic capacity of leaves. Incident PPFD for each leaf in the canopy was evaluated as a function of cumulative LAI with Eq. 5. The extinction coefficient (K) changed depending on stands: Abutilon, 1.12 and 0.76; Ambrosia, 1.02 and 1.07; mixed stands, 1.12 and 0.94 on day 39 and 53, respectively. There was no significant difference in K between the two CO2 levels (data not shown). Transmittance (τ) was determined for each leaf with Eq. 2 and a leaf N–chlorophyll relationship (Eq. 10). Fig. 5 shows daily rates of canopy photosynthesis of Abutilon and Ambrosia in monospecific and mixed stands grown under ambient and elevated CO2 conditions. CO2 elevation increased daily canopy photosynthesis by 30–50%. On day 39 Ambrosia had higher canopy photosythesis than Abutilon, whereas the difference was diminished between the two monospecific stands on day 53. This is due to the faster leaf area development with higher N content in Ambrosia (Fig. 1), enabling this species to attain higher photosynthetic rates. There was no significant difference in leaf area and leaf N between the two species on day 53.

Estimated values of canopy photosynthesis (Fig. 5) were strongly correlated with rates of carbon gain (r2 = 0.77, n = 8; Fig. 6) measured using growth analysis in the same stands (growth analysis data from Fig. 3 in Hirose et al. 1996b). The correspondence between these two measurements is particularly striking, as the photosynthetic parameters used to parameterize our model were obtained from plants grown independently of those used for growth analysis (see Materials and methods). In addition, four of the eight data points were from mixed-species stands in which a simple linear model of light interception was used to estimate the relative performance of the two species. These results validate the structure and parameterization of our model for predicting canopy-level photosynthesis, and support its use for the assessment of optimal LAI below.

Discussion

Modeling of leaf photosynthesis

Rectangular hyperbolic equations fit the present data for Pmax–NL relationships better than the linear equations that have been used by many authors (e.g., Hirose and Werger 1987a, Pons et al. 1990, Anten et al. 1995b). Curvilinear relationships between Pmax and NL were also obtained by several authors (Gulmon and Chu 1981, Evans 1983, Makino et al. 1988, Hilbert et al. 1991, Hikosaka and Terashima 1995). Diminishing returns of carbon gain with increasing NL may be due to increased PPFD limitation at higher NL. Hirose and Werger (1987a) showed strong curvilinear relationships between net photosynthesis and NL when PPFD was low. Our plants were grown in the glasshouse with maximum PPFD less than 1200 μmol·m−2·s−1 and Pmax was measured at a PPFD of 1000–1200 μmol·m−2·s−1, which might have still limited photosynthesis of leaves with high NL. Leaf photosynthesis significantly increased with CO2 elevation. Proportional increase in Pmax with CO2 elevation, however, was higher at higher NL. The 20–30% increase found in the range of NL = 1.0–1.5 g N/m2 in Abutilon is in good agreement with a review of Cure and Acock (1986) who showed that doubling CO2 led, on average, to a 29% increase in leaf photosynthesis after acclimation. Tissue et al. (1995) reported that Abutilon grown in elevated CO2 increased net photosynthesis by 27% relative to growth at ambient CO2. Because NL was not increased with CO2 elevation, the increase in leaf photosynthesis with CO2 elevation was solely due to increased photosynthetic activity per unit leaf N.

Linear equations were applied to the relationships between Rd and NL. A linear relationship is expected if protein turnover represents a major fraction of maintenance respiration in the canopy (Penning de Vries 1975). Several authors have reported linear relationships between Rd and NL (Hirose and Werger 1987a, Pons et al. 1990, Anten et al. 1995b). CO2 elevation slightly but significantly increased Rd in Abutilon, while no significant difference was found in Rd of Ambrosia. No consistent results have been reported on the effect of CO2 elevation on Rd (Amthor 1997): Rd increased in perennial ryegrass (Nijs et al. 1988) and cotton (Thomas et al. 1993), decreased in Rumex crispus (Amthor et al. 1992) and soybean (Bunce and Ziska 1996), or was not significantly changed in plantain (Poorter et al. 1988) and a saltmarsh sedge (Long and Drake 1991). Increase in carbohydrate supply with CO2 elevation does not seem to lead to increased Rd (see Lambers 1985, Farrar and Williams 1991).

Quantum yield calculated on an absorbed light basis (φabs) is a function of (a) the efficiency of energy transduction into NADPH (reduced form of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate) and ATP (adenosine triphosphate) on the photosynthetic membrane and (b) the metabolic pathways in which this reducing and phosphorylating potential is utilized (Long and Drake 1991). In the ambient atmospheric CO2 concentration, φabs shows remarkable constancy among C3 species, while in an atmosphere with an elevated CO2 concentration, φabs is expected to rise in proportion to the increase in the ratio of carboxylations of RuBP (ribulose-1,5-bis-phosphate) to oxygenations (Farquhar et al. 1980). In this paper we assumed φabs = 0.05 at the atmospheric CO2 concentration of 360 μL/L and φabs = 0.07 at 700 μL/L following the data in Ehleringer and Björkman (1977). They obtained these values in a short-term experiment. Long and Drake (1991) suggested that tissues developed in an elevated CO2 atmosphere show an acclimatory decrease in φabs and reported φabs = 0.065 (351 μL/L) and 0.078 (680 μL/L) in Scirpus olneyi. Thus, the difference in φabs between the two CO2 levels may be smaller than that used in our model (see sensitivity analysis in Optimal LAI below). The initial slope was a saturating function of NL. Pons et al. (1990) obtained the initial slope as a rectangular hyperbolic function of NL through regression, while Hikosaka and Terashima (1995) derived such functions from their model of optimal N allocation among photosynthetic proteins.

Nitrogen distribution and canopy photosynthesis

Applying the leaf photosynthesis model to the actual distribution of leaf area and N through the canopy, we calculated daily rates of canopy photosynthesis of the monospecific and mixed stands of Abutilon and Ambrosia. Distribution of leaf N in the canopy (Fig. 1) reflects leaf area distribution and N content per leaf area (NL). At the later growth stage when the canopy was fully developed, NL was higher in upper layers in the canopy, and thus the mode of leaf N shifts to a higher position than the mode of leaf area distribution (Hirose et al. 1988, 1989). Higher NL in upper layers is due to reallocation of N from lower layers with canopy development. Such reallocation leads to maximization of photosynthetic returns of the whole canopy, because leaves in the microenvironments receiving the highest PPFD have the highest N concentration (Field 1983, Hirose and Werger 1987b). The coefficient of N allocation (Ka; Hirose and Werger 1987b) increased from 0.01 to 0.51 in Abutilon and 0.42 to 0.88 in Ambrosia in the period from day 39 to 53. Increase in Ka with stand development was also observed in Carex acutiformis (Hirose et al. 1989). Ambrosia had higher Ka than Abutilon (P < 0.01), but no significant effect of doubling CO2 on Ka was observed. Ka did not change in either species when grown in a mixed stand. Anten et al. (1995a) showed that the optimal pattern of N allocation in the canopy is determined by the extinction coefficient for light and the total amount of free (i.e., translocatable) N, and is independent of the slope of Pmax against NL. The absence of a significant CO2 effect on Ka in this experiment is consistent with this prediction, since elevated CO2 altered the slope of Pmax–NL relationships, while other characteristics such as K and leaf N remained virtually unchanged, though the actual distribution of N is always more uniform than the optimal one (data not shown).

Rates of canopy carbon gain based on growth analysis were 40–50% lower than those based on physiological parameters (Fig. 6). This difference may be accounted for by several factors, including consumption of photosynthates in respiratory processes of nonphotosynthetic organs (Lambers 1985), exclusion of root mass from growth analysis, which might have led to ∼10% underestimation (cf. Coleman and Bazzaz 1992), and reductions due to cloudiness during the growth period, as the calculated values assumed full sun. Assumption of average diffuse PPFD in the canopy (Eq. 5) in the calculations would also overestimate photosynthesis because of the convex photosynthesis–light response curve (Spitters 1986). CO2 elevation increased daily canopy photosynthesis by 30–50%, which is comparable to a 25–45% increase in a mixed-meadow model ecosystem (Overdieck and Lieth 1986), 54% increase in a rice stand (Allen et al. 1989), 77% increase in perennial ryegrass (Nijs et al. 1988), and 40–88% increase in a salt marsh community (Drake and Leadley 1991). The increase in growth rate under high CO2 conditions (Hirose et al. 1996b) was explained by the increased photosynthetic rate per leaf area, which in turn was explained by the increase in photosynthetic N use efficiency of leaves. Photosynthetic N use efficiency would increase by 60% with doubling CO2 if leaf N was optimally partitioned among photosynthetic proteins (K. Hikosaka, personal communication).

Optimal LAI

The present experiment did not show an increase in LAI with CO2 elevation. Hirose et al. (1996b) hypothesized that leaf area development is controlled by N availability rather than by atmospheric CO2 concentrations. This hypothesis is consistent with a recent experiment on the effect of CO2 and N availability in rice plants (Ziska et al. 1996), in which LAI increased with increasing addition of N but not with CO2 elevation at equal levels of N availability. Hättenschwiler and Körner (1996) also showed that the rate of leaf area production was not significantly changed by CO2, but was significantly increased with the rate of N supply in understory plants. However, several authors predicted an increase in LAI with CO2 elevation, because CO2 elevation leads to an increase in the initial slope of the light-response curve and thus to a reduction of the light compensation point (LCP; Pearcy and Björkman 1983, Long and Drake 1991). A reduced LCP would allow additional leaf area development deep in the canopy and increase overall LAI. However, LCP depends on the change in dark respiration as well as the initial slope. The LCP may increase if CO2 elevation increases dark respiration. The other factor that might be involved in determining the LAI at high CO2 is N availability. If the availability of N is limited, N may be reallocated faster to the top of the canopy, counteracting the hypothesis of improved carbon balance in shade leaves (Long and Drake 1991). In a preliminary analysis we found that optimal LAI did not change greatly under elevated CO2 (Hirose et al. 1996a). In the rest of this paper we will examine the effect of CO2 elevation on the optimal LAI in relation to N availability and evaluate the relative sensitivity of optimal LAI and canopy photosynthesis to variation in leaf photosynthetic parameters. Studying optimal LAI helps understand the factors that determine LAI and is thus an ideal approach to elucidate the mechanism by which CO2 elevation influences LAI.

For a fixed amount of leaf area and N availability for leaf growth, daily canopy photosynthesis is maximized when in every microsite in the canopy, the rate of change of daily carbon gain with changing leaf N is equal:
((11))
∂PL,day/∂NL = λ
where PL,day is daily carbon gain of a leaf in the canopy and λ is a Lagrange multiplier (Field 1983). Eq. 11 defines the optimal distribution of N through the canopy. On the other hand, we consider optimal LAI to be the LAI that maximizes the daily rate of canopy photosynthesis for a fixed amount of N.

Fig. 7a–f shows daily canopy photosynthesis as a function of LAI for a given amount of N available for leaf growth (Nt), in which N distribution is optimized according to Eq. 11. Here canopy photosynthesis and leaf N are presented per unit ground area. (Since there were 100 plants/m2, division by 100 gives daily canopy photosynthesis per plant, which is comparable to Fig. 5.) In the calculation, parameter values in the leaf photosynthesis model of Abutilon were utilized (Eqs. 8a, b, 9a, b, and 10a with Eqs. 1 and 2) and K = 1.0 was assumed. Fig. 7a, d shows daily rates of canopy photosynthesis with optimal distribution of leaf N at ambient and elevated CO2, respectively. For each N availability, there was an optimal LAI that maximized the canopy photosynthesis. The optimal LAI increased with increasing N availability both in ambient and elevated CO2, but actually decreased with increasing atmospheric CO2 concentration, contradicting the often predicted increase in LAI with CO2 elevation (Pearcy and Björkman 1983, Long and Drake 1991). Although the actual distribution of leaf N in a canopy is always more uniform than the optimal distribution, the optimal LAI showed fairly good agreement with the values that were observed at corresponding N levels (Fig. 4a in Hirose et al. 1996a). Daily canopy photosynthesis increased with increasing N availability, and then declined at the highest N levels (due to increasing respiratory costs of high NL). CO2 elevation increased daily canopy photosynthesis, but the extent to which the canopy photosynthesis increases is larger at higher Nt. Differences in the daily canopy photosynthesis between ambient and elevated CO2 shown in Fig. 7a, d are due to the difference in three parameters of leaf photosynthesis (Pmax, φabs, and Rd). Next we conduct a sensitivity analysis of each leaf photosynthetic parameter to evaluate why the optimal LAI did not increase with CO2 elevation.

In Fig. 7b, e, the values of φabs were exchanged, relative to Fig. 7a, d (φabs = 0.07 in Fig. 7b and φabs = 0.05 in Fig. 7e), while the other parameters of leaf photosynthesis remained unchanged. As a result, ambient CO2 values for Pmax and Rd are associated with the elevated CO2 values for φabs in Fig. 7b, and vice versa in Fig. 7e. Increase in φabs from 0.05 to 0.07 increased the canopy photosynthesis, and the extent of increase in canopy photosynthesis is larger at higher LAI (compare Fig. 7b with a, Fig. 7e with d). This is because most leaves in the canopy with high LAI are light limited, and the increase in φabs improved their photosynthetic rates considerably (Long and Drake 1991). On the other hand, increasing Pmax as well improved canopy photosynthesis across the entire range of LAI (compare Fig. 7b with f, Fig. 7c with e). Note that the optimal LAI was not increased but tended to decrease with the increase in φabs. This rather unexpected result was derived from a shift in the balance between light and N limitation of leaf photosynthesis in the canopy (Anten et al. 1995a, Goudriaan 1995): With increase in φabs, the light use efficiency of leaves increases and at a given light availability (i.e., position in the canopy) leaves become more light saturated and therefore more N limited in the canopy. For those leaves, the positive effects of increase in NL on leaf- and thus on whole-canopy photosynthesis will increase.When N availability is limited, higher N content per leaf area necessarily leads to lowering of LAI. On the other hand, low efficiency of light use in leaves with low φabs indicates that more leaves in the canopy are light limited and thus the photosynthetic benefits of increasing NL will be less. For those leaves further development of leaf area is favored to increase the whole-canopy photosynthesis by intercepting more light with concomitant reduction in N content per leaf area. The effect of dark respiration on the canopy photosynthesis was evaluated by exchanging values of Rd in ambient and elevated CO2 (Fig. 7a and d), while leaving the other parameters the same (Fig. 7c and f). An increase in Rd decreased canopy photosynthesis (compare Fig. 7c with a; Fig. 7d with f). Optimal LAI tended to decrease with increasing Rd, which is simply explained by the reduction of LCP because φabs was not changed. Theoretically, increase in photosynthetic N use efficiency at elevated CO2 should increase optimal LAI (Anten et al. 1995a), but this effect seems relatively small. In summary, two factors are involved in the reduction in the optimal LAI in a high-CO2 world when N availability is limited (Fig. 7a,d). One is the higher φabs of plants grown in elevated CO2, which makes more leaves N limited in the canopy, favors higher NL, and lowers optimal LAI. The other is the higher Rd in elevated CO2,which leads to larger LCP, and lowers optimal LAI. These factors apparently mitigate the effects of an increase in the initial slope of the light-response curve, and emphasize that predictions based on leaf-level considerations will not necessarily hold true at the canopy- and whole-plant level. As a result optimal LAI does not increase with the elevation of atmospheric CO2 concentration when N availability for plant growth is limited.
